# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heavy-light-decomposition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] In combinatorial mathematics and theoretical computer science, **heavy-light decomposition** (also called **heavy path decomposition**) is a technique for decomposing a rooted tree into a set of paths.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] In a heavy path decomposition, each non-leaf node selects one "heavy edge", the edge to the child that has the greatest number of descendants (breaking ties arbitrarily).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] The selected edges form the paths of the decomposition.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Leaf nodes of the tree that are not the endpoint of a heavy edge may be considered as forming paths of length zero.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] In this way, each vertex belongs to exactly one of the paths.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Each path has a head vertex, its topmost vertex.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Alternatively, the paths of heavy edges may be extended by including one light edge, the one from the head of the path to its parent.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] In this variation of the decomposition, some vertices belong to multiple paths, but every edge of *T* belongs to exactly one path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] The paths of the decomposition may themselves be organized into a tree called the "path tree", "heavy path tree", or "compressed tree".
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Each node of the path tree corresponds to a path of the heavy path decomposition.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] If *p* is a path of the heavy path decomposition, then the parent of *p* in the path tree is the path containing the parent of the head of *p*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] The root of the path tree is the path containing the root of the original tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Alternatively, the path tree may be formed from the original tree by edge contraction of all the heavy edges.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] A "light" edge of a given tree is an edge that was not selected as part of the heavy path decomposition.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] If a light edge connects two tree nodes *x* and *y*, with *x* the parent of *y*, then *x* must have at least twice as many descendants as *y*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Therefore, on any root-to-leaf path of a tree with *n* nodes, there can be at most log2 *n* light edges.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] Equivalently, the path tree has height at most log2 *n*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/heavy-path-decomposition] In the lowest common ancestor data structure, the decomposition is used to embed the input tree into a complete binary tree of logarithmic depth, allowing each query to be solved by constant-time bitwise operations.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The represented forest may consist of very deep trees, so if we represent the forest as a plain collection of parent pointer trees, it might take us a long time to find the root of a given node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] However, if we represent each tree in the forest as a link/cut tree, we can find which tree an element belongs to in *O*(log(*n*)) amortized time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Moreover, we can quickly adjust the collection of link/cut trees to changes in the represented forest.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In particular, we can adjust it to merge (link) and split (cut) in *O*(log(*n*)) amortized time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Link/cut trees divide each tree in the represented forest into vertex-disjoint paths, where each path is represented by an auxiliary data structure (often splay trees, though the original paper predates splay trees and thus uses biased binary search trees).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The nodes in the auxiliary data structure are ordered by their depth in the corresponding represented tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In one variation, *Naive Partitioning*, the paths are determined by the most recently accessed paths and nodes, similar to Tango Trees.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In *Partitioning by Size* paths are determined by the heaviest child (child with the most children) of the given node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This gives a more complicated structure, but reduces the cost of the operations from amortized O(log n) to worst case O(log n).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] It has uses in solving a variety of network flow problems and to jive data sets.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In the original publication, Sleator and Tarjan referred to link/cut trees as "dynamic trees", or "dynamic dyno trees".
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We take a tree where each node has an arbitrary degree of unordered nodes and split it into paths.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] These paths are represented internally by auxiliary trees (here we will use splay trees), where the nodes from left to right represent the path from root to the last node on the path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Nodes that are connected in the represented tree that are not on the same preferred path (and therefore not in the same auxiliary tree) are connected via a *path-parent pointer*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This pointer is stored in the root of the auxiliary tree representing the path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] When an access to a node *v* is made on the *represented tree*, the path that is taken becomes the **preferred path**.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The **preferred child** of a node is the last child that was on the access path, or null if the last access was to *v* or if no accesses were made to this particular branch of the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] A **preferred edge** is the edge that connects the **preferred child** to *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In an alternate version, preferred paths are determined by the heaviest child.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The operations we are interested in are `FindRoot(Node v)`, `Cut(Node v)`, `Link(Node v, Node w)`, and `Path(Node v)`.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Every operation is implemented using the `Access(Node v)` subroutine.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] When we *access* a vertex *v*, the preferred path of the represented tree is changed to a path from the root *R* of the represented tree to the node *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] If a node on the access path previously had a preferred child *u*, and the path now goes to child *w*, the old *preferred edge* is deleted (changed to a *path-parent pointer*), and the new path now goes through *w*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] After performing an access to node *v*, it will no longer have any preferred children, and will be at the end of the path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since nodes in the auxiliary tree are keyed by depth, this means that any nodes to the right of *v* in the auxiliary tree must be disconnected.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In a splay tree this is a relatively simple procedure; we splay at *v*, which brings *v* to the root of the auxiliary tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We then disconnect the right subtree of *v*, which is every node that came below it on the previous preferred path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The root of the disconnected tree will have a path-parent pointer, which we point to *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We now walk up the represented tree to the root *R*, breaking and resetting the preferred path where necessary.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] To do this we follow the path-parent pointer from *v* (since *v* is now the root, we have direct access to the path-parent pointer).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] If the path that *v* is on already contains the root *R* (since the nodes are keyed by depth, it would be the left most node in the auxiliary tree), the path-parent pointer will be null, and we are done the access.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Otherwise we follow the pointer to some node on another path *w*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We want to break the old preferred path of *w* and reconnect it to the path *v* is on.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] To do this we splay at *w*, and disconnect its right subtree, setting its path-parent pointer to *w*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since all nodes are keyed by depth, and every node in the path of *v* is deeper than every node in the path of *w* (since they are children of *w* in the represented tree), we simply connect the tree of *v* as the right child of *w*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We splay at *v* again, which, since *v* is a child of the root *w*, simply rotates *v* to root.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We repeat this entire process until the path-parent pointer of *v* is null, at which point it is on the same preferred path as the root of the represented tree *R*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] FindRoot refers to finding the root of the represented tree that contains the node *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since the *access* subroutine puts *v* on the preferred path, we first execute an access.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Now the node *v* is on the same preferred path, and thus the same auxiliary tree as the root *R*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since the auxiliary trees are keyed by depth, the root *R* will be the leftmost node of the auxiliary tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So we simply choose the left child of *v* recursively until we can go no further, and this node is the root *R*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The root may be linearly deep (which is worst case for a splay tree), we therefore splay it so that the next access will be quick.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Here we would like to cut the represented tree at node *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This puts all the elements lower than *v* in the represented tree as the right child of *v* in the auxiliary tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] All the elements now in the left subtree of *v* are the nodes higher than *v* in the represented tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We therefore disconnect the left child of *v* (which still maintains an attachment to the original represented tree through its path-parent pointer).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Now *v* is the root of a represented tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Accessing *v* breaks the preferred path below *v* as well, but that subtree maintains its connection to *v* through its path-parent pointer.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] If *v* is a tree root and *w* is a vertex in another tree, link the trees containing *v* and *w* by adding the edge(v, w), making *w* the parent of *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] To do this we access both *v* and *w* in their respective trees, and make *w* the left child of *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since *v* is the root, and nodes are keyed by depth in the auxiliary tree, accessing *v* means that *v* will have no left child in the auxiliary tree (since as root it is the minimum depth).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Adding *w* as a left child effectively makes it the parent of *v* in the represented tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] For this operation we wish to do some aggregate function over all the nodes (or edges) on the path from root *R* to node *v* (such as "sum" or "min" or "max" or "increase", etc.).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] To do this we access *v*, which gives us an auxiliary tree with all the nodes on the path from root *R* to node *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The data structure can be augmented with data we wish to retrieve, such as min or max values, or the sum of the costs in the subtree, which can then be returned from a given path in constant time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Cut and link have *O*(1) cost, plus that of the access.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] FindRoot has an *O*(log *n*) amortized upper bound, plus the cost of the access.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The data structure can be augmented with additional information (such as the min or max valued node in its subtrees, or the sum), depending on the implementation.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Thus Path can return this information in constant time plus the access bound.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So it remains to bound the *access* to find our running time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Access makes use of splaying, which we know has an *O*(log *n*) amortized upper bound.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So the remaining analysis deals with the number of times we need to splay.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This is equal to the number of preferred child changes (the number of edges changed in the preferred path) as we traverse up the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We bound *access* by using a technique called **Heavy-Light Decomposition**.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This technique calls an edge heavy or light depending on the number of nodes in the subtree. ⁠ $Size(v)$ ⁠ represents the number of nodes in the subtree of *v* in the represented tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] An edge is called *heavy* if size(v) > 1⁄2 size(parent(v)).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Thus we can see that each node can have at most 1 *heavy* edge.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] An edge that is not a *heavy* edge is referred to as a *light* edge.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The *light-depth* refers to the number of light edges on a given path from root to vertex *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] *Light-depth* ≤ lg *n* because each time we traverse a light-edge we decrease the number of nodes by at least a factor of 2 (since it can have at most half the nodes of the parent).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So a given edge in the represented tree can be any of four possibilities: *heavy-preferred*, *heavy-unpreferred*, *light-preferred* or *light-unpreferred*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] First we prove an $O(\log ^{2}n)$ upper bound.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The splay operation of the access gives us log *n*, so we need to bound the number of accesses to log *n* to prove the *O*(log 2 *n*) upper bound.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Every change of preferred edge results in a new preferred edge being formed.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So we count the number of preferred edges formed.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Since there are at most log *n* edges that are light on any given path, there are at most log *n* light edges changing to preferred.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] The number of heavy edges becoming preferred can be ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ for any given operation, but it is ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠ amortized.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Over a series of executions we can have *n*-1 heavy edges become preferred (as there are at most *n*-1 heavy edges total in the represented tree), but from then on the number of heavy edges that become preferred is equal to the number of heavy edges that became unpreferred on a previous step.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] For every heavy edge that becomes unpreferred a light edge must become preferred.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We have seen already that the number of light edges that can become preferred is at most log *n*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] So the number of heavy edges that become preferred for *m* operations is ⁠ $m(\log n)+(n-1)$ ⁠.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Over enough operations (⁠ $m>n-1$ ⁠) this averages to ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We have bound the number of preferred child changes at ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠, so if we can show that each preferred child change has cost O(1) amortized we can bound the *access* operation at ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] This is done using the potential method.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Let s(v) be the number of nodes under *v* in the tree of auxiliary trees.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Then the potential function $\Phi =\sum _{v}\log {s(v)}$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] We know that after splaying, *v* is the child of its path-parent node *w*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] where *R* is the root of the represented tree, and we know the number of preferred child changes is ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Link/cut trees can be used to solve the dynamic connectivity problem for acyclic graphs.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Given two nodes x and y, they are connected if and only if FindRoot(x) = FindRoot(y).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] Another data structure that can be used for the same purpose is Euler tour tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/link-cut-tree] In solving the maximum flow problem, link/cut trees can be used to improve the running time of Dinic's algorithm from $O(V^{2}E)$ to $O(VE\log V)$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The LCA of v and w in T is the shared ancestor of v and w that is located farthest from the root.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In a tree data structure where each node points to its parent, the lowest common ancestor can be easily determined by finding the first intersection of the paths from v and w to the root.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In general, the computational time required for this algorithm is O(h) where h is the height of the tree (length of longest path from a leaf to the root).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] However, there exist several algorithms for processing trees so that lowest common ancestors may be found more quickly.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Tarjan's off-line lowest common ancestors algorithm, for example, preprocesses a tree in linear time to provide constant-time LCA queries.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In general DAGs, similar algorithms exist, but with super-linear complexity.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The lowest common ancestor problem was defined by Alfred Aho, John Hopcroft, and Jeffrey Ullman (1973), but Dov Harel and Robert Tarjan (1984) were the first to develop an optimally efficient lowest common ancestor data structure.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Their algorithm processes any tree in linear time, using a heavy path decomposition, so that subsequent lowest common ancestor queries may be answered in constant time per query.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] However, their data structure is complex and difficult to implement.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Tarjan also found a simpler but less efficient algorithm, based on the union-find data structure, for computing lowest common ancestors of an offline batch of pairs of nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Baruch Schieber and Uzi Vishkin (1988) simplified the data structure of Harel and Tarjan, leading to an implementable structure with the same asymptotic preprocessing and query time bounds.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The structure of Schieber and Vishkin decomposes any tree into a collection of paths, such that the connections between the paths have the structure of a binary tree, and combines both of these two simpler indexing techniques.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Omer Berkman and Uzi Vishkin (1993) discovered a completely new way to answer lowest common ancestor queries, again achieving linear preprocessing time with constant query time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] They then handle this range minimum query problem (RMQ) by combining two techniques, one technique based on precomputing the answers to large intervals that have sizes that are powers of two, and the other based on table lookup for small-interval queries.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] This method was later presented in a simplified form by Michael Bender and Martin Farach-Colton (2000).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] As had been previously observed by Gabow, Bentley & Tarjan (1984), the range minimum problem can in turn be transformed back into a lowest common ancestor problem using the technique of Cartesian trees.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Further simplifications were made by Alstrup et al.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Sleator and Tarjan (1983) proposed the dynamic LCA variant of the problem in which the data structure should be prepared to handle LCA queries intermixed with operations that change the tree (that is, rearrange the tree by adding and removing edges).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] This variant can be solved in $O(\log N)$ time in the total size of the tree for all modifications and queries.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] This is done by maintaining the forest using the dynamic trees data structure with partitioning by size; this then maintains a heavy-light decomposition of each tree, and allows LCA queries to be carried out in logarithmic time in the size of the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] As mentioned above, LCA can be reduced to RMQ.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] An efficient solution to the resulting RMQ problem starts by partitioning the number sequence into blocks.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Two different techniques are used for queries across blocks and within blocks.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Reduction of LCA to RMQ starts by walking the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] For each node visited, record in sequence its label and depth.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Suppose nodes *x* and *y* occur in positions *i* and *j* in this sequence, respectively.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Then the LCA of *x* and *y* will be found in position RMQ(*i*, *j*), where the RMQ is taken over the depth values.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Despite that there exists a constant time and linear space solution for general RMQ, but a simplified solution can be applied that make uses of LCA’s properties.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] This simplified solution can only be used for RMQ reduced from LCA.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Similar to the solution mentioned above, we divide the sequence into each block $B_{i}$ , where each block $B_{i}$ has size of $b={1 \over 2}\log n$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] To answer the $RMQ(i,j)$ query in case one, there are 3 groups of variables precomputed to help reduce query time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] First, the minimum element with the smallest index in each block $B_{i}$ is precomputed and denoted as $y_{i}$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Second, given the set of $y_{i}$ , the RMQ query for this set is precomputed using the solution with constant time and linearithmic space.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] There are $n/b$ blocks, so the lookup table in that solution takes $O({n \over b}\log {n \over b})$ space.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, the precomputed RMQ query using the solution with constant time and linearithmic space on these blocks only take $O(n)$ space.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Third, in each block $B_{i}$ , let $k_{i}$ be an index in $B_{i}$ such that $0\leq k_{i}<b$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Then the minimum element with the smallest index for intervals in $[0,k_{i})$ and $[k_{i},b)$ in each block $B_{i}$ is precomputed.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Such minimum elements are called as prefix min for the interval in $[0,k_{i})$ and suffix min for the interval in $[k_{i},b)$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Each iteration of $k_{i}$ computes a pair of prefix min and suffix min.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, the total number of prefix mins and suffix mins in a block $B_{i}$ is $2b$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Since there are $n/b$ blocks, in total, all prefix min and suffix min arrays take $O(2b\cdot {n \over b})$ which is $O(n)$ spaces.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In total, it takes $O(n)$ space to store all 3 groups of precomputed variables mentioned above.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Let $B_{i}$ be the block that contains the element at index i , and $B_{j}$ for index j .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] All 3 questions can be answered in constant time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, case 1 can be answered in linear space and constant time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The sequence of RMQ that reduced from LCA has one property that a normal RMQ doesn’t have.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The next element is always +1 or -1 from the current element.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Therefore, each block $B_{i}$ can be encoded as a bitstring with 0 represents the current depth -1, and 1 represent the current depth +1.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] This transformation turns a block $B_{i}$ into a bitstring of size $b-1$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] A bitstring of size $b-1$ has $2^{b-1}$ possible bitstrings.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, $B_{i}$ is always one of the ${\sqrt {n}}$ possible bitstring with size of $b-1$ .
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Then, for each possible bitstring, we apply the naïve quadratic space constant time solution.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Therefore, answering the $RMQ(i,j)$ query in case 2 is simply finding the corresponding block (in which is a bitstring) and perform a table lookup for that bitstring.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Hence, case 2 can be solved using linear space with constant searching time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] While originally studied in the context of trees, the notion of lowest common ancestors can be defined for directed acyclic graphs (DAGs), using either of two possible definitions.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In both, the edges of the DAG are assumed to point from parents to children.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] In a tree, the lowest common ancestor is unique; in a DAG of n nodes, each pair of nodes may have as much as *n*-2 LCAs (Bender et al.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] 2005), while the existence of an LCA for a pair of nodes is not even guaranteed in arbitrary connected DAGs.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] A brute-force algorithm for finding lowest common ancestors is given by Aït-Kaci et al.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] (1989): find all ancestors of x and y, then return the maximum element of the intersection of the two sets.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Better algorithms exist that, analogous to the LCA algorithms on trees, preprocess a graph to enable constant-time LCA queries.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The problem of *LCA existence* can be solved optimally for sparse DAGs by means of an O(|*V*||*E*|) algorithm due to Kowaluk & Lingas (2005).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] (2013) present a unified framework for preprocessing directed acyclic graphs to compute *a representative* lowest common ancestor in *a rooted DAG* in constant time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] Their framework can achieve near-linear preprocessing times for sparse graphs and is available for public use.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The problem of computing lowest common ancestors of classes in an inheritance hierarchy arises in the implementation of object-oriented programming systems (Aït-Kaci et al.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/lowest-common-ancestor] The LCA problem also finds applications in models of complex systems found in distributed computing (Bender et al.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **path** in a graph is a finite or infinite sequence of edges which joins a sequence of vertices which, by most definitions, are all distinct (and since the vertices are distinct, so are the edges).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] A **directed path** (sometimes called **dipath**) in a directed graph is a finite or infinite sequence of edges which joins a sequence of distinct vertices, but with the added restriction that the edges be all directed in the same direction.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Paths are fundamental concepts of graph theory, described in the introductory sections of most graph theory texts.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] (1990) cover more advanced algorithmic topics concerning paths in graphs.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] ) has a first vertex but no last vertex.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] If there is a finite walk between two *distinct* vertices then there is also a finite trail and a finite path between them.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Some authors do not require that all vertices of a path be distinct and instead use the term **simple path** to refer to such a path where all vertices are distinct.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] A weighted graph associates a value (*weight*) with every edge in the graph.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] The *weight of a walk* (or trail or path) in a weighted graph is the sum of the weights of the traversed edges.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Sometimes the words *cost* or *length* are used instead of weight.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Similarly for a directed trail or a path.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] If there is a finite directed walk between two *distinct* vertices then there is also a finite directed trail and a finite directed path between them.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] A "simple directed path" is a path where all vertices are distinct.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] A weighted directed graph associates a value (*weight*) with every edge in the directed graph.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] The *weight of a directed walk* (or trail or path) in a weighted directed graph is the sum of the weights of the traversed edges.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Several algorithms exist to find shortest and longest paths in graphs, with the important distinction that the former problem is computationally much easier than the latter.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] Dijkstra's algorithm produces a list of shortest paths from a source vertex to every other vertex in directed and undirected graphs with non-negative edge weights (or no edge weights), whilst the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be applied to directed graphs with negative edge weights.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] The Floyd–Warshall algorithm can be used to find the shortest paths between all pairs of vertices in weighted directed graphs.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/path-graph-theory] The **k-path partition** problem is the problem of partitioning a given graph to a smallest collection of vertex-disjoint paths of length at most *k*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] This means that [*x*, *x′*] spans the whole interval from the left endpoint of Int(*v*1) to the right endpoint of Int(*v*3).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Note that all segments at a particular level are non-overlapping and ordered from left to right: this is true by construction for the level containing the leaves, and the property is not lost when moving from any level to the one above it by combining pairs of adjacent segments.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Now either parent(*v*2) = parent(*v*1), or the former is to the right of the latter (edges in the tree do not cross).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] In the first case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is the same as Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point; in the second case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is to the right of Int(parent(*v*1))'s rightmost point, and therefore also to the right of Int(*v*1)'s rightmost point.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] In both cases, Int(parent(*v*2)) begins at or to the right of Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Similar reasoning shows that Int(parent(*v*2)) ends at or to the left of Int(*v*3)'s rightmost point.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] Int(parent(*v*2)) must therefore be contained in [*x*, *x′*]; hence, [*x*, *x′*] will not be stored at *v*2.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces, in the form of multi-level segment trees.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] In higher dimensional versions, the segment tree stores a collection of axis-parallel (hyper-)rectangles, and can retrieve the rectangles that contain a given query point.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The structure uses *O*(*n* log*d* *n*) storage, and answers queries in *O*(log*d* *n*) time.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The use of fractional cascading lowers the query time bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/segment-tree] The use of the interval tree on the deepest level of associated structures lowers the storage bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] In computer science, a **tree** is a widely used abstract data type that represents a hierarchical tree structure with a set of connected nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Each node in the tree can be connected to many children (depending on the type of tree), but must be connected to exactly one parent, except for the *root* node, which has no parent (i.e., the root node as the top-most node in the tree hierarchy).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] These constraints mean there are no cycles or "loops" (no node can be its own ancestor), and also that each child can be treated like the root node of its own subtree, making recursion a useful technique for tree traversal.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] In contrast to linear data structures, many trees cannot be represented by relationships between neighboring nodes (parent and children nodes of a node under consideration, if they exist) in a single straight line (called edge or link between two adjacent nodes).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Binary trees are a commonly used type, which constrain the number of children for each parent to at most two.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] When the order of the children is specified, this data structure corresponds to an ordered tree in graph theory.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A value or pointer to other data may be associated with every node in the tree, or sometimes only with the *leaf nodes*, which have no children nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The abstract data type (ADT) can be represented in a number of ways, including a list of parents with pointers to children, a list of children with pointers to parents, or a list of nodes and a separate list of parent-child relations (a specific type of adjacency list).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Representations might also be more complicated, for example using indexes or ancestor lists for performance.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Trees as used in computing are similar to but can be different from mathematical constructs of trees in graph theory, trees in set theory, and trees in descriptive set theory.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A node is a structure which may contain data and connections to other nodes, sometimes called **edges** or **links**.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Each node in a tree has zero or more **child nodes**, which are below it in the tree (by convention, trees are drawn with *descendants* going downwards).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A node that has a child is called the child's **parent node** (or superior).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] All nodes have exactly one parent, except the topmost **root node**, which has none.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A node might have many **ancestor nodes**, such as the parent's parent.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Child nodes with the same parent are **sibling nodes**.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Typically siblings have an order, with the first one conventionally drawn on the left.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Some definitions allow a tree to have no nodes at all, in which case it is called *empty*.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] An **internal node** (also known as an **inner node**, **inode** for short, or **branch node**) is any node of a tree that has child nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Similarly, an **external node** (also known as an **outer node**, **leaf node**, or **terminal node**) is any node that does not have child nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The **height** of a node is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The height of the root is the height of the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The **depth** of a node is the length of the path to its root (i.e., its *root path*).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Thus the root node has depth zero, leaf nodes have height zero, and a tree with only a single node (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Conventionally, an empty tree (tree with no nodes, if such are allowed) has height −1.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Each non-root node can be treated as the root node of its own **subtree**, which includes that node and all its descendants.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from child to parent.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from parent to child.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] For a given node, its number of children.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The degree of a tree is the maximum degree of a node in the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The number of edges along the shortest path between two nodes.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] The level of a node is the number of edges along the unique path between it and the root node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A tree with every level filled, except the last.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Stepping through the items of a tree, by means of the connections between parents and children, is called **walking the tree**, and the action is a *walk* of the tree.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Often, an operation might be performed when a pointer arrives at a particular node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] There are many different ways to represent trees.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] In working memory, nodes are typically dynamically allocated records with pointers to their children, their parents, or both, as well as any associated data.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] If of a fixed size, the nodes might be stored in a list.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Nodes and relationships between nodes might be stored in a separate special type of adjacency list.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] In relational databases, nodes are typically represented as table rows, with indexed row IDs facilitating pointers between parents and children.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Nodes can also be stored as items in an array, with relationships between them determined by their positions in the array (as in a binary heap).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] A binary tree can be implemented as a list of lists: the head of a list (the value of the first term) is the left child (subtree), while the tail (the list of second and subsequent terms) is the right child (subtree).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] This can be modified to allow values as well, as in Lisp S-expressions, where the head (value of first term) is the value of the node, the head of the tail (value of second term) is the left child, and the tail of the tail (list of third and subsequent terms) is the right child.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Ordered trees can be naturally encoded by finite sequences, for example with natural numbers.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] 4 has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] B has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] In terms of type theory, a tree is an inductive type defined by the constructors nil (empty forest) and node (tree with root node with given value and children).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Viewed as a whole, a tree data structure is an ordered tree, generally with values attached to each node.
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Often trees have a fixed (more properly, bounded) branching factor (outdegree), particularly always having two child nodes (possibly empty, hence *at most* two *non-empty* child nodes), hence a "binary tree".
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] Allowing empty trees makes some definitions simpler, some more complicated: a rooted tree must be non-empty, hence if empty trees are allowed the above definition instead becomes "an empty tree or a rooted tree such that ...".
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] On the other hand, empty trees simplify defining fixed branching factor: with empty trees allowed, a binary tree is a tree such that every node has exactly two children, each of which is a tree (possibly empty).
[src:heavy-light-decomposition/tree-data-structure] JSON and YAML documents can be thought of as trees, but are typically represented by nested lists and dictionaries.
